│ I'll search for code that handles `SExtInst` and `ZExtInst` and how they are grouped. The logic for building the "graph" of scalars to be vectorized is a good candidate. The function   │
│ `BoUpSLP::getVectorElement` or similar functions that build the vectorizable tree are relevant.                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core of the SLP vectorizer's bottom-up building process is to see if it can form a vector instruction from a set of scalar instructions. When it encounters an instruction, say `I`, │
│ it checks if `I` and its lane-partner scalars can be represented as a vector instruction. For a `sext` instruction, it will look at other lanes and see if they are also `sext`s from a  │
│ vector operand.                                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem is that the vectorizer is trying to be too aggressive. It's trying to vectorize a `sext` and a `zext` together. This should be prevented. The check that determines if two   │
│ instructions can be vectorized together needs to be more strict.                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Looking at the `SLPVectorizer.cpp` file, the function `BoUpSLP::canMapToVector` seems relevant. It checks if a set of scalars can be mapped to a vector instruction. Inside this         │
│ function, or in a function it calls, there should be a check for the opcode.                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A key function is `BoUpSLP::getVectorElement(Value *V)`. It tries to find or build a vectorizable entry for a given scalar value `V`. When `V` is an instruction, it will try to group   │
│ it with others.                                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let's look at how `CastInst` is handled. The function `BoUpSLP::canMapToVector` has a switch on the opcode. For `Instruction::SExt`, `Instruction::ZExt`, and `Instruction::Trunc`, it   │
│ calls `canMapToVector(CI, Scalars)`.                                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem is likely in how the vectorizer decides that two instructions are of the "same kind". The `alive2` output shows it's trying to form a vector of `sext`s. This means it has   │
│ identified `sext` as the target vector opcode and is trying to fit the `zext` into that mold, which is incorrect.                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The check `isSplat(Scalars)` is important. If all scalars are the same, it's a splat. If not, it tries to build from vector operands. The logic for this is in                           │
│ `BoUpSLP::getVectorElement`.                                                                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The function `BoUpSLP::canMapToVector` has this logic:                                                                                                                                   │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ // Check if all of the scalars are the same instruction.                                                                                                                                 │
│ Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Scalars[0]);                                                                                                                                      │
│ //...                                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ for (unsigned i = 1, e = Scalars.size(); i != e; ++i) {                                                                                                                                  │
│   Instruction *In = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Scalars[i]);                                                                                                                                   │
│   if (!In || !In->isSameOperationAs(I))                                                                                                                                                  │
│     return false;                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ }                                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ `isSameOperationAs` checks for opcode, type, and for some instructions, other properties. For `CastInst`, it checks `getOpcode()`. This means `SExt` and `ZExt` are correctly identified │
│ as different.                                                                                                                                                                            │
